		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> A In-depth X-list from 7/6/04<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(3.58)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=17333'>Philly "KingChoke" Kemp</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=17333&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> July 10, 2004</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> In this article, I will talk about the cards that have been x-listed and some reasons why they deserve to be banned. This article is for the people who get mad when their favorite card is x-ed. I will try and explain the best to my ability why they are banned. <br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
Aggression:<br />
Well here is a card that I even got a little ticked off about when I herd that it had been <br />
x-ed. One of the reasons is that is only cost 1 to play and make each Dwarf Damage +1<br />
where as “Lord of Moria” cost 2 to make each Dwarf Damage +1. But I thought about it for a while and I realized why it was banned. Because of it’s second text. Yes, the one that can let you draw cards. Let’s do an example…<br />
<br />
Your opponent plays an Aggression from his hand in his Fellowship phase.<br />
This makes it where he has 4 Aggression out. You are at site 8 and he or she is at site 7.<br />
He knows that the only way to win is to double move. But the problem is, is that he does not have any pumps or any cards that can possibly keep his Ring-bearer alive. But then he spots his 4 Aggression. It says “Fellowship: Spot a Dwarf who is Damage +X to draw <br />
X cards. Lets say he spots his Durin bearing “Ring of Fury” (Damage +2), and Gimli’s Battle Axe, Trusted Weapon (If you can spot a threat, bearer is Damage +1). Then Durin<br />
is already Damage +1. Durin is a Damage +4. Then he sees that he has initiative (which makes it where each Dwarf is Damage +1, from Aggression). Since he has 4 of them out,<br />
Durin is Damage +8. He then discards 1 Aggression to discard 8 cards (even though he has to discard one of the conditions, you still count the discarded Aggression as a Damage +1). That’s eight cards! Not only that but he has 3 more left. He discards another<br />
and then draws 7 cards. Another then draws 6 cards. Then the last and draws 5 cards.<br />
This is a total of 26 cards. He still may not be able to draw all of them since he may not<br />
have that many cards left in his deck. But still, that’s a lot of cards. He draws the pumps he needs and the weapons to put on his dwarves. At site 9, Gimli is exhausted. You lose by a hair when he plays a pump at site 9 on his Ring-bearer Gimli so that he does not take a wound from the minion. He is not killed because of the pumps he drew from Aggression. <br />
<br />
Now this set-up is unlikely to happen, but it’s just a scenario.<br />
Now, hopefully you understand why Aggression was banned.<br />
<br />
<br />
Aragorn, Heir to the White City<br />
<br />
In my opinion, I believe that he should be taken off the banned list because he <br />
really is only broken when used with the broken cards “No Strangers to the Shadow”.<br />
But since he is banned, I tell you why the banned him.<br />
He has only 1 text so this is why he is banned. He says “When the Fellowship moves <br />
in the Fellowship Phase, remove 2.” This is good I guess when used in a choke<br />
deck. He might be broken when played in a dwarf choke deck. Here is a example…<br />
<br />
Your has out Gimli (Ring-bearer), Durin, Sindri, and Aragorn, HttWC. He plays lots of<br />
free dwarf weapons. The last thing he plays is a “Lord of Moria” which costs 2. He then<br />
moves to site 3 that costs one. But he removes the twilight that was there (Since Lord of Moria was the only “Twilight Costing” thing, and it cost 2, Aragorn gets to remove 2 when you move in the fellowship phase, which he did). You now only have 5 twilight <br />
instead of 7. He removed enough to pay the roaming penalty for a minion (if you play Nazgul or Dunlend, this doesn’t apply.)<br />
<br />
This is why he is banned.<br />
<br />
No Strangers to the Shadows:<br />
This is a really broken card since it’s not unique. It says “Bearer must be a Ranger. Limit<br />
1 per bearer. The site number of each site is –1.” This is also a Gondor card. BUT, it says<br />
bearer must be a Ranger. It doesn’t say “Bearer must be a (Gondor)ranger.” This allows No Strangers to be played on the Ranger Arwen. The main reason it is banned is that it’s not unique. You can play up to 4. Here is an example…<br />
<br />
Your opponent has out Isildur (Ring-bearer), Aragorn, Ranger of the North, Arwen,<br />
Daughter of Elrond, Boromir, Lord of Gondor, and Faramir, Son of Denethor.<br />
He already has out 2 No Strangers at site 4. He plays out 2 more and a few other cards.<br />
In just the fellowship phase, he gives you 4 twilight. He would move to site 5 for 6, except with the 4 No Strangers, he now moves to site 5 for –4. So your total twilight is<br />
now 11 instead of 15. That’s a big difference in twilight.<br />
<br />
It’s banned because it’s not unique.<br />
<br />
Bill the Pony:<br />
I would not be surprised if this was taking off the banned list. It says,<br />
“Bearer must be a Hobbit companion. The Site number is –1.” This card is unique. You may think this card should not be banned because it is unique and you can only make the <br />
site number –1. Well, back before Reflections came out, the only Ring-bearer there was<br />
is Frodo. Bill could fit in to any deck. It was easy to put it in because you didn’t have to play Pippin, Sam, or Merry. All you had to do is play Frodo, which you had to play.<br />
Now since there are new Ring-bearers, it would be harder to fit it in a deck.<br />
<br />
<br />
The big, fat, ugly “FRYING PAN”<br />
It says “ Bearer must a Hobbit. Exert bearer to wound an orc.” This hand weapon adds<br />
1 to the strength. Anyone who played a Moria swam deck despised this card. It’s ability<br />
to be played on Frodo and kill every minion on him when you where going for a swarm.<br />
Here is an example…<br />
<br />
Your opponent has out 4 companions which none of them are able to be defender +1.<br />
You play out 6 minions. Your opponent can’t kill any of you Moria orcs in the archery <br />
 or Maneuver phase. Your opponent can only assign 4 and you have 2 extra to assign.<br />
You don’t notice your opponent’s Frying Pan. You place them on a fully healed Frodo.<br />
You know it’s over. Your opponent completes the other skirmishes and then goes to Frodos’. You suddenly see that annoying Frying Pan half slid under The One Ring. You have 15 strength on your opponents 4 strength Frodo. You would overwhelm him except<br />
for that he has Frying Pan. Each of your orcs have 1 vitality. Frodo exerts 2 times from<br />
Frying Pan to wound 2 of your orcs. 2 are dead and 1 measly 5 strength is left. You win the skirmish and Frodo takes a burden instead of a wound.<br />
<br />
How bad would that be knowing you emptied out you hand you have been saving up just<br />
to get smacked by the evil “Pan”<br />
<br />
Saruman, Keeper of Isengard:<br />
<br />
He says, “Saruman may not be assigned to a skirmish and may not take wounds during<br />
the archery phase. Uruk-hia are fierce. Response: If an Uruk-hai is about to take a wound, exert Saruman to prevent that wound.” He has 8 strength, 4 vitality, twilight cost<br />
is 4, his race is Wizard, and his site number is 4.<br />
This guy is the king of his Uruk-hai. As soon as you play him, all of your Uruk-hai become fierce. Even the ones you play after him are fierce. Not only that but he can<br />
keep them alive long enough until the fierce skirmish. He totally techs against archery. Plus, he can’t take wounds in the archery phase. That means that the FP player can’t target archery wounds to him and make it where he can’t exert to prevent wounds.<br />
No need for an example because he is just plain broken.<br />
<br />
Elrond, Lord of Rivinndel:<br />
<br />
He says “At the start of each of your turns, heal every site 3 ally once. Fellowship:<br />
Exert Elrond to draw a card.” He cost 4, has 8 strength, 4 vitality, is an ally, home site<br />
3, and is just plain broken.<br />
Like Aggression, Elrond lets you draw a lot of cards. The first time you use him, you could draw up to 3 cards. If you played “The Tale of Gil-galad” and “Aiglos” on him,<br />
that would put him to 6 vitality and let you draw 5 cards. Then next turn he would heal<br />
himself once and draw another card. BUT that’s not all. Notice how he heals EVERY<br />
SITE 3 ALLY once. This goes for site 3 allies that aren’t even from the Elven culture.<br />
This means that you could use the allies text more than once or twice. This is a really<br />
good reason why he is banned (although it’s mostly for the drawing cards). There isn’t<br />
really any cards that heal allies (especially when there was just Fellowship, Mines, and <br />
Relams out), so this is a really good text.<br />
<br />
Galadriel, Lady of Light:<br />
<br />
This is another broken elf ally. She says, “At the start of each of your turns, you may heal<br />
every ally who home site is 6 once. Fellowship: Exert Galadriel to play an Elf for free.”<br />
<br />
Like Elrond, she heals allies. But she heals site 6 allies. But that’s not the part that is <br />
just broken. The “Free” part is the most broken. This is an incredible choking ability.<br />
Also, you could put “The Tale of Gil-galad”, “Nenya”, and “Aiglos” to make Galadriel<br />
vitality 6. You could play up to 5 Elves from you hand for Free the first time you use<br />
her. Then she heals herself at the start of your next turn so she can play another Elf for free.<br />
<br />
Ottar:<br />
<br />
He says, “To play, spot Gandalf. Regroup: Exert Ottar to discard up to 3 cards and then<br />
draw an equal amount.” He is a site 3 ally, 2 strength, 2 vitality, and Gandalf culture.<br />
<br />
He a really good cycler. He allows you to discard cards (in the regroup) to draw the same<br />
amount of cards you discarded. This is good if you are about to stay and don’t have any good minion cards. Here is an example…<br />
<br />
Your opponent just stopped moving at site 7. He had 3 cards left in his hand. He knew that you were at site 8 and was going to win if he couldn’t get out at least 7 minions. But<br />
he had 3 cards left. They were all Free Peoples cards. He could only draw 6 cards. That’s <br />
not enough minions and he has no way of drawing any cards. But then he spots Ottar. He exerts him to discard the 3 FP cards in his hand. He then draws 3 cards. 2 are minions, the<br />
other a FP card. He reconciles the FP card and the draws 6 cards. All 6 are minions. You play a few cards then move to site 9 for 9 twilight. You give him a total of 15.<br />
He’s playing moria swarm. He plays out 7 minions and beats you by swarm.<br />
<br />
If it hadn’t been for those extra 2 cards from Ottar, he wouldn’t of been able to beat you.<br />
<br />
<br />
Savagery to Match Their Numbers:<br />
<br />
It says, “Skirmish: Make an Uruk-hia strength +2, or strength +4 and fierce, if you can<br />
spot 5 companions.” <br />
<br />
This event is the best pumper for an Uruk-hai (maybe not as much since “Sack of the Shire” came out). Since no one really plays more than 5 companions because of Enquea,<br />
they usually only play 5. This is where Savagery is at it’s best. It makes an Uruk-hai strength +4 and fierce. This can totally kill your Fellowhip if you do play more than 5 companions. <br />
<br />
Relics of Moria:<br />
<br />
It says, “Plays to your support area. Shadow: Remove 2 to play a (Moria) weapon from<br />
you discard pile.” It costs 1 and is a condition.<br />
<br />
This is an incredible card for a Moria swarm deck. If you had out just 2 Goblin Armories, you could use it’s text for free (armories adds 1 twilight each time you play<br />
a (Moria) weapon. Since there is 2 out, this sort of cancels out the Relics cost.) If you have already used your scimitars, and they are in the discard pile and you have no scavengers in your hand to get back them, you can just play them with Relics. Then you can draw cards. They could be more minions. This increases the chance of swarm.<br />
<br />
Ulaire Nertea, Messenger of Dul Golder:<br />
<br />
He says, “When you play this minion, you may play a minion from your discard for each<br />
companion you can spot over 4.” He costs 4, and is a Nazgul/Minion.<br />
<br />
This is an incredible card, again, for swarm. If you played a big fellowship, this guy would kill you. He would work good because you could play any minion you want from<br />
your discard pile. If you played a large Fellowship, he could play a lot from his discard pile. <br />
<br />
Forces of Mordor:<br />
<br />
It says, “Shadow: Spot X (Sauron) minions to add X.” It’s an event and costs 0.<br />
<br />
This is a too good card for Sauron swarm. Since they are roaming for a while, they take<br />
up a lot of twilight. If you were to play out a couple trackers, and then play some more (without the roaming penalty because of the trackers) you might be able to get out quite a few. But you still may not have enough twilight. Here is an example…<br />
<br />
You have out 5 companions, (Frodo is your Ring-bearer). You move to site 5 and his total twilight is 13. He plays out 2 trackers for 6 (this makes it where they aren’t roaming<br />
any more). He plays out 3 more trackers for 6 twilight. He has 1 twilight left but only<br />
5 minions out against your 5 companions. That’s not enough to swarm. He has 3 cards left in his hand. 2 are minions and the other is Forces of Mordor. He plays Forces to add<br />
5 twilight because he can spot 5 of his (Sauron) minions. This makes it where he has 6 twilight to spend. He plays out the other to minions and swarms you.<br />
<br />
Broken, huh.<br />
<br />
Sting (Fellowship Sting)<br />
<br />
It says, “Bearer must be Frodo. Fellowship of Regroup: Exert Frodo to reveal an<br />
opponents hand. Remove 1 for each Orc revealed.” It costs 1, and is a Hand Weapon.<br />
<br />
This is a really good card. The Fellowship of the Ring “Glamdring” has the same text<br />
except  that bearer has to be Gandalf. Back when Frodo was the only Ring-bearer, Sting<br />
could fit in to any deck. Glamdring wasn’t banned because in order to use it, you had to play Gandalf, where as Sting could fit in to any deck, because Frodo had to be in any deck. What’s really good about this card is it’s ability to look at an opponents hand. There isn’t many cards that allow this. Plus, it removes twilight for each Orc revealed in<br />
opponents hand. There are a lot of different kinds of orcs. Orcs are popular too. This card<br />
kills swarm because the most popular swarm is Moria (Orc) and Sauron (Orc).<br />
Sauron really needs twilight (which Sting cancels out) and Moria needs a little bit.<br />
You can also use this text in the Regroup, when you are about to move again.<br />
This card is just too good.<br />
<br />
Horn of Boromir:<br />
<br />
It says, “Bearer must be Boromir. Maneuver: Exert Boromir and spot an ally. Until the<br />
regroup phase, that ally is strength +3 and participates in archery and in skirmishes.” It<br />
costs 0 and is just a possession.<br />
<br />
This is just way to broken. I can see why decipher banned it. This makes it where it is almost impossible to swarm. Plus, you can practically exert Boromir to add 1 to the archery total (since when you exert him, that ally participates in archery fire). Also, he<br />
makes an ally strength +3. He can make Elrond shoot archery, participate in skirmishes,<br />
and make him an 11 strength just from one exertion. <br />
<br />
The Palantir of Orthanc:<br />
<br />
It says, “To play, spot an (Isengard) minion. Plays to your support area. Shadow: Spot<br />
an (Isengard) minion, and remove 1, to reveal a card at random from opponents hand.<br />
Place that card on top of owners draw deck.” It is an artifact, the culture is Isengard, it costs 0.<br />
<br />
This is one of the most annoying cards to play against. Why it was banned is because you<br />
were able to place cards back on there draw deck. This makes it hard to draw “new” cards since all the cards that was in your hand, were moved to the top of your draw deck. When you go to draw cards, you have to draw the cards that were placed there before you can draw new cards. Here is an example…<br />
<br />
You play 2 cards in your Fellowship phase to give your opponent 3 twilight. Then you<br />
move to site 6 for 3. You have out 4 companions. You give your opponent a total of 10<br />
twilight. Your opponent only has 1 thing to play, which costs 3. Since he has nothing else to play, he removes 6 twilight to put all the cards you have in your hand on top of your <br />
draw deck. You go to the regroup phase and decide to stay. Since you have no cards in your hand, you draw a full 8. You only draw 2 new cards and you are stuck with the cards you could do nothing with. It would happen like this anyway even if your opponent had not used the Palantir, but since he did, it made it where you had nothing to reconcile and decreased the chances of moving again because you could have lost you vital pumpers.<br />
<br />
Put this card in a side deck and play against it. It’s very annoying, especially if you get 1<br />
early in the game.<br />
<br />
<br />
Here are 2 newer cards banned.<br />
<br />
Steadfast Champion:<br />
It says, “Bearer must be Gandalf. Each minion gains this ability, “Assignment: Assign<br />
this minion to Gandalf”. Regroup: Discard this condition to discard a minion and heal<br />
a companion 3 times.” <br />
<br />
Ouch! This card lets you discard a minion (which may help you move again) and you get to heal a companion three times. (The minion does not gain the regroup text. Only Gandalf does.) Here is an example…<br />
<br />
Your opponent has out 3 companions, which one is Gandalf bearing “Steadfast Champion”. You played out 3 minions in the shadow phase. Your opponent exhausted<br />
his Aragorn (using his bow) to kill one of the 3 vitality minions. He is at site 8, and needs to kill off all the minions for a decent double move. But you assign your 13 strength minion to Gandalf because of the “Steadfast Champion”. The other is assigned and killed.<br />
Gandalf takes a wound from the skirmish. He needs to get rid of the 13 strength minion<br />
before he can move. But he has to move because he has 6 cards in his hand and only 1 of them is a minion. You are at site 8. You would win if he didn’t move again. But if he didn’t get rid of the minion he could possibly get swarmed by moving to the most expensive site in the game. Plus, his Aragorn can’t kill any more minions because he has 3 wounds on him and is exhausted. But, your opponent spots “Steadfast Champion” and decides to use it. He discards the fully healthy 13 strength minion and heals Aragorn 3 times. Aragorn is fully healed and there are no minion left. Since you only played 3 minions, you have 5 cards left. You discard a FP card and draw 4 cards. 4 are minions.<br />
You can afford them all. You play them. Aragorn kills of 1. The rest are assigned to the 3 companions and he wins the game. If wasn’t for the fully healing Gorn with his bow and discarding a minion, you would have won.<br />
<br />
Last one, don’t worry.<br />
<br />
Gondorian Captain:<br />
<br />
He says, “Knight. Discard a fortification to remove a threat.” He is strength 6, vitality 3, and he cost 2.<br />
<br />
He is a really good threat removal card. There are tons of different fortifications that you can discard. Plus, it could help get unique fortifications out of your hand. Here is an example…<br />
<br />
Your opponent has out a Gondorian Captain. He has out the unique fortification out called “Stone Tower”. He has 2 other in his hand. He is at site 3 (which is “while you cannot spot 3 threats, add a threat to draw a card). He adds 3 threats to draw 3 cards.<br />
Then he uses his Captain and discards the “Stone Tower” to remove a threat. This makes it where he can draw an extra card. He adds a threat to draw that card. He then plays another “Stone Tower”. He uses his Captain again to remove a threat. He draws a card and then plays out a new fortification he just drew. He then plays his last “Stone Tower” from his hand. This just got rid of the 2 cards that where clogging his hand. Plus he drew another fortification. He discards them both to remove 2 threats and then adds them both back to draw 2 more cards. This cycle could go on for a while.<br />
<br />
Now you see why this guy is banned.<br />
<br />
<br />
Whew, it has been a long, and fun article. I apologize if I typed in some wrong info, but I don’t work at decipher so I’m not sure how everything card works.<br />
<br />
Hopefully I did a good job on this 8 page article.<br />
<br />
Happy playing!! <br />
<br />
&quot;KingChoke&quot; <br />
